<h1>@HI{{koto}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}} @EM{{@HI{{koto}}}}
<li> @Ai{{}} @EM{{@HI{{koto}}}}
<li> @Ana{{}} @EM{{@HI{{koto}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{koto}}}} is a nominaliser that indicates the speaker's relative lack of empathy with the
content of the nominalised sentence.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{koto}}}} turns a whole sentence into a noun phrase which can then be used anywhere that a noun
phrase can normally be used.
</p>

<p>
Unlike the nominaliser <a href="grammar-no-nominaliser.html">@HI{{no}}</a>, @EM{{@HI{{koto}}}} tends to indicate
something to which the speaker does not feel very close.
</p>

<p>
In the pattern:
<br/>
A@HI{{ha}}B@HI{{desu}}
<br/>
<string>@HI{{koto}}</strong> can be used in position B but @HI{{no}} cannot.
</p>

<p>
The pattern
<br/>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}no@KJ{{gist^flavor}}ha}}@Vru{{}}@HI{{@EM{{koto}} desu.}}
<br/>
can be used to better define a hobby.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{suisu}}ga kireina@EM{{koto}}ha @KJ{{copy^true}}de @KJ{{know}}tteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      From photographs I know that Switzerland is beautiful.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}no@KJ{{gist^flavor}}ha @KJ{{sound^music}}wo @KJ{{hear}}ku @EM{{koto}} desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      My hobby is listening to music.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
There are various structures where @EM{{@HI{{koto}}}} is used and @HI{{no}} is not:
<ul>
<li> ... @HI{{ha @EM{{koto}} desu.}}
<li> ... @HI{{@EM{{koto}} ga aru}} ...
<li> ... <a href="grammar-koto-ga-dekiru.html">@HI{{@EM{{koto}} ga dekiru}} ... </a>
<li> ... @HI{{@EM{{koto}} ni naru}} ...
<li> ... @HI{{@EM{{koto}} ni suru}} ...
<li> ... @HI{{@EM{{koto}} ha}} ...
</ul>
</p>

